The paper deals with the algorithmic complexity of a problem related to sequences, specifically the Longest Common Increasing Subsequence problem. This problem involves finding the longest increasing subsequence that is common to multiple sequences. The paper presents tight lower bounds for this problem assuming the Strong Exponential Time Hypothesis (SETH). The problem involves data structures (cs.DS), computational complexity (cs.CC), computational geometry (cs.CG), and discrete mathematics (cs.DM). The paper also involves information theory (cs.IT) in its analysis of the lower bounds.
